      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5003290269f83199",
      "text": "Figure 3. Pixels, points and rectangles, x increases to the right, and y downwards. The squares are pixels, and the dots their centers. The point (x, y) labels the pixel centered at (x+tt, y+%). A rectangle is specified by two points, its origin and corner, and includes those pixels whose centers it contains.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "aed9b63f4fd48dee",
      "text": "If p is the point (k, /), then X[p] and Y[p] denote respectively the x and y components of p, that is, k and I. For brevity, we will sometimes write px and py for X[p] and Y[p]. A rectangle r is defined by a pair of points r=(o, c), the origin o and comer c, as shown in Figure 3. We assume that ox^cx and oy^Cy. We also write o =origin[r] and c=comer[r]. A non-empty rectangle is said to contain those pixels whose centers it contains. Since rectangles have sides positioned at integer coordinates and pixels are centered at half-integer coordinates, this notion is unambiguous. Another useful attribute of a rectangle is its extent, defined by […]\n "
